b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe01040.htm)  [Next](sbe01042.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBW6/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 1 (SBE01)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### SEVENTH KHA _N_ _D_ A.\n\n1\\. Let a man meditate on the fivefold Saman, which is greater than great, as\nthe pra _n_ as (senses). The hi\xe1\xb9\x85kara is smell 1 (nose), the prastava speech\n(tongue), the udgitha sight (eye), the pratihara hearing (ear), the nidhana\nmind. These are one greater than the other.\n\n2\\. What is greater than great belongs to him, nay, he conquers the worlds\nwhich are greater than\n\np. 26\n\ngreat, who knowing this meditates on the fivefold Saman, which is greater than\ngreat, as the pra _n_ as (senses).\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[25:1](sbe01041.htm#fr_132) Pra _n_ a is explained by ghra _n_ a, smell;\npossibly ghra _n_ a may have been the original reading. Anyhow, it cannot be\nthe mukhya pra _n_ a here, because it is distinctly represented as the lowest\nsense.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: II, 8](sbe01042.htm)\n\n'